<div id="review_2744635454" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2744635454" />
    <a title="Ben" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7283807-ben"><img alt="Ben" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1538334787p2/7283807.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2744635454?book_show_action=true">May 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ben" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ben" href="/user/show/7283807-ben">Ben</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7283807-ben?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2744635454" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17765173093223998495">This is an intriguing biography. I learned a lot, clearing up my own fuzzy impressions. But I read this after Roberts&apos;s Churchill biography, and it just doesn&apos;t compare. Partly, Roberts doesn&apos;t do as good a job here in conveying the historical environment around Napoleon. In a movie, it would be a tight shot of Napoleon&apos;s face, with everything else out of focus, for the whole show. <br/><br/>Partly, though, Napoleon actually isn&apos;t as interesting a character as Churchill. The Churchill biography is filled </span>
  <span id="freeText17765173093223998495" style="display:none">This is an intriguing biography. I learned a lot, clearing up my own fuzzy impressions. But I read this after Roberts's Churchill biography, and it just doesn't compare. Partly, Roberts doesn't do as good a job here in conveying the historical environment around Napoleon. In a movie, it would be a tight shot of Napoleon's face, with everything else out of focus, for the whole show. <br /><br />Partly, though, Napoleon actually isn't as interesting a character as Churchill. The Churchill biography is filled with little anecdotes that show his personality—his wit or his drive. For example, "Just before reaching the Virginia coast, Churchill told Captain Cecil Harcourt that he would like to see the Duke of York sail at full speed, scornful of the objection that the water was shallow and it would send up an immense wash. At 28 knots, a massive stern wave was created which, because someone had left the scuttles open, flooded several rooms between decks, including the Admiral’s cabin that Churchill used, and he had to shave with his trousers rolled above his knees, ‘humming a little tune to himself’, Vivian Cox recalled. ‘He knew he had really been rather naughty.’" <br /><br />Roberts tries to find anecdotes here, too, doing so by drawing on some recently available letters from Napoleon. But they just aren't as interesting. They usually take the form of Napoleon micromanaging something back in Paris (a play, a trial) while out on campaign; or of Napoleon complaining about his troops' shoes. "During the first three months of 1807, … The subject of shoes and boots generated sixty-three letters." This is interesting to learn the first time, but by the tenth time Roberts points out a similar letter it is just boring. <br /><br />The second conceit of the biography, besides Roberts's access to Napoleon's letters, is that Roberts himself traveled through Europe, visiting all the major battlefields. He brings this out in the prose, talking about how in person a hill is more imposing than the elevation would suggest, or about how a particular memorial is right next to a McDonalds parking lot. This is a gimmick, of course, but for me it works. It's just not enough. The individual battles interest me less than Napoleon as a character and the broader context. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17765173093223998495" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


