<div id="review_1734433791" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1734433791" />
    <a title="Corey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5603545-corey"><img alt="Corey" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1734433791?book_show_action=true">Sep 11, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Corey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Corey" href="/user/show/5603545-corey">Corey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1734433791" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1529414569560144692">This biography was extremely thorough and quite interesting, but I found it a bit of a slog. While I commend Roberts for packing so much into a single book, I feel like it was so dense that the readability was negatively impacted. For example, because so much of the text focuses on Napoleon&apos;s time as a general, numbers regarding casualty counts are given for nearly every single battle. What&apos;s more, hundreds of names of places and people are included, but not all of them are lasting settings or &quot;</span>
  <span id="freeText1529414569560144692" style="display:none">This biography was extremely thorough and quite interesting, but I found it a bit of a slog. While I commend Roberts for packing so much into a single book, I feel like it was so dense that the readability was negatively impacted. For example, because so much of the text focuses on Napoleon's time as a general, numbers regarding casualty counts are given for nearly every single battle. What's more, hundreds of names of places and people are included, but not all of them are lasting settings or "characters." Essentially, it was hard to keep track of which names I should try to remember and which ones would never return. <br /><br />In this vein, readers should have a reasonable grasp of 18th and 19th century European geography and politics or be prepared to check maps or Wikipedia - I have a general idea of where everything is in Europe, but there were so many city names that it was often hard to follow which path Napoleon had taken or where he was fighting in relation to other battles. This challenge, combined with my relatively weak knowledge of the European states of the period, made things a little difficult to follow. <br /><br />Perhaps it is unfair of me to want Roberts to spell everything out for me, but I think some of the highly specific details could have easily been swapped out for a bit more big picture explanation or analysis and I would have enjoyed the text a lot more.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1529414569560144692" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


